<subSubSection id="C374652CFFBBFFD0D4CCFF740E4AFE8E" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BD136A7FFBBFFD0D4CCFF740E4AFE8E" blockId="70.[151,1437,151,393]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="B91AEAB5FFBBFFD0D4CCFF740C16FF6A" bold="true" box="[199,334,223,249]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a patronymic in honor of the Indian arachnologist John Caleb by his contributions to the taxonomy of the Jumping spiders of 
<collectingCountry id="F3797637FFBBFFD0D6DAFEA80E56FE8E" box="[721,782,259,285]" name="India" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C374652CFFBBFFD0D4CCFE8D0878FE1A" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BD136A7FFBBFFD0D4CCFE8D0878FE1A" blockId="70.[151,1437,151,393]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="B91AEAB5FFBBFFD0D4CCFE8D0C1AFED3" bold="true" box="[199,322,294,320]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D24FFBBFFD0D5A4FE8C0F0BFED2" authority="Martínez &amp; Brescovit &amp; Quijano, 2022" authorityName="Martínez &amp; Brescovit &amp; Quijano" authorityYear="2022" box="[431,595,295,321]" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Tenedos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calebi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B91AEAB5FFBBFFD0D5A4FE8C0F0BFED2" box="[431,595,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Tenedos calebi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B91AEAB5FFBBFFD0D651FE8C0FC0FED2" bold="true" box="[602,664,295,321]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22957CEFFBBFFD0D651FE8C0FC0FED2" box="[602,664,295,321]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are distinguished by median apophysis (MA) with small anterior projection, bifid retrolateral tibial apophysis (RTA), anterior branch (aRTA) laminar, popsicle stick-shaped, posterior branch (pRTA) short, wide; tegulum with small, sclerotized prolateral projection (
